entry.title: [Thumbnail Cache] Ignore Aspect Ratio for Refactor
entry.content:
Rather than forcing JPEGs to be of a specific aspect ratio when

captured just capture the viewport and scale it by a factor of 2.



Use a matrix in TabGridViewBinder and MultiThumbnailCardProvider to

correctly crop the bitmap for display. This could use slightly more

memory, but has the upshot of skipping resize entirely and avoid the

need to refetch on rotation changes as the existing bitmap (or the

one being captured) are the best available options anyway.



Based on local testing memory usage was the same within a margin of

5 MB lower for the change. However, in my experience a fluctuation of

up to 10 MB even with forced GC is possible so it is pretty difficult

to say whether this has a net positive or negative effect on memory.

We can observe this during experimentation to see the effect.



When requesting a JPEG do the following:

1) If a capture is in progress wait for it.

2) Otherwise just fetch the JPEG and use a matrix to crop it.



The benefits of this are:

1) We can entirely remove ETC1 decompression and JPEG recompression.

2) Aspect ratio is no longer relevant in the capture code making

it simpler and may be more performant (less bitmap copying).

3) Have some cropped margin for the JPEG so when displayed in the

orientation/aspect ratio the image was not captured for it

doesn't look as unappealing.



Also remove the save_jpeg_thumbnails param. This has been effectively

defaulted to true for a very long time. There is an argument to be

made that on low-end devices where we will show the list version of

the Grid Tab Switcher we could skip recording JPEGs. However, if

we want to do this a better alternative is to just check whether the

device is low-end rather than setting a param.

entry.title: Reland "[ios] Add support for copy-to-surface"
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit 275f990d792575a0f47866d41aac8ad9e3961fde



To see what I've changed in the reland, please check out:

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4600124/1..5



It includes blundell@'s fix from crrev.com/c/4594556 (I'd broken

graphite, accidentally, in my first attempt).



Other noteworthy changes

- We compile out autoscroll-related tests (see comments; I think

the same rationale for ignoring this on Android applies for iOS).

- We ensure that we initialize our screen infos when we construct

our RWHVIOS (without this, we initially have the wrong DSF set).

- We also respect the DSF override (without this, many tests fail).

- We no longer check for integer DSF in ui_resource. In practice,

we should only get integer DSFs, but a handful of tests set non-

integer DSF. We could include "test-only" in these DCHECKs, but

since the ui resource code is robust to non-integer scales (it

finds the nearest applicable resource set), there seems to be no

harm in allowing them.



Original change's description:

> [ios] Add support for copy-to-surface

> This exposed a situation where we can have a mismatch in buffer formats

> between compositing and skia, so I've also added plumbing to ensure

entry.title: Adjust criteria for showing select commands in touch selection menu.
entry.content:
Disable the select all and select word commands in the touch selection

menu if we know that there is no text to select. Also disable the select

all command if we know that all text has already been selected. If we

don't know the text range that can be selected, keep the current

behaviour.



Also fix the behaviour of HandleContextMenu when tapping an empty

textfield while no menu commands are enabled. In this case,

TouchSelectionControllerClientAura does not show a menu but should still

handle the context menu request. (This is just fixing the code initially

added in crrev.com/c/4520088 that didn't account for the select commands

being disabled.)



For testing, just add to the existing browser tests for now. Will add a

tast test and probably also an interactive ui test for the touch

selection menu behaviour in a followup (eventually).

entry.title: Fixes regression in Media.Audio.Processing.CaptureDelayMs
entry.content:
This CL fixes an issue where input audio timestamps were "faked" even

when that was not needed. This leads to very small capture delays

(~1ms) in the AudioProcessor.



With this change, the AP will measure ~10-11 milliseconds on most

audio devices as before.



Note that, there will still be some devices where the QPC-based

timestamp method will not work and that will probably reduce the

Media.Audio.Processing.CaptureDelayMs over time going forward.

entry.title: Reland "[Enrollment] Mock EnrollmentLauncher with a factory."
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit 0090223f92fb1a29f3b3ccf2638c382836b69ab3



The problem with original commit was that MockEnrollmentLauncher has to

outlive its tested consumers.



The reland adds better lifetime handling of EnrollmentScreen,

DemoSetupController and MockEnrollmentLauncher in unittests. Browsertest

already have satisfying lifetime.



Now in unit tests, lifetime of mock and tested consumer are managed via

construction order:

1. In EnrollmentScreenUnitTest, mocks are regular non-pointer members

initialized before enrollment screen. Except for MockErrorScreen which

has to be reset in TearDown() before network portal shutdown.

Enrollment screen is also destroyed in TearDown() as it requires

browser process shutdown.

2. In DemoSetupControllerTest, mocks are regular non-pointer members

initialized before tested DemoSetupController.

3. In DemoSetupControllerTest, task environment moved to be the first

member so that all other members (specifically

DemoSetupControllerTestHelper) use it.

4. All mocks are wrapped with NiceMock to prevent unused warnings.



Original change's description:

> [Enrollment] Mock EnrollmentLauncher with a factory.

>

> In tests, enrollment launcher was mocked via global mock holder. Tests

> used to set a mock before it is yanked by

> EnrollmentLauncher::Create function called by a launcher's consumer

> (e.g. enrollment screen). It was one time set after which tests needed

> to set another mock, and had to know when to do so.

>

> Now, tests have full control and access to the launcher's mock and can

> easily set and reset expectations. Tests have no care about when

> fake enrollment launchers, connected to the mock, are created and used.

> Tests can inject fake enrollment launchers via factory override.

>

entry.title: Revert "Reland "Reland "pthreadpool: Integrate with Jobs API"""
entry.content:
This reverts commit bbef2b40c9e20a4c8ad121ddac95abe6347389f9.



Reason for revert: Speculative fix for crbug.com/1454009, multiple

tests are failing



Original change's description:

> Reland "Reland "pthreadpool: Integrate with Jobs API""

>

> This is a reland of commit 9fd417a399dfb28ace5add2fa7df714f70de5bb6

>

> The pthreadpoool library is built with "sanitizers:cfi_icall_disable"

> config that would cause pthreadpool_unittests failure on the Linux CFI

> bot, such as [1]. This reland enables the cfi-icall sanitizer flag by

> removing this config. It also fixes a pointer cast issue in

> pthreadpool_unittests.

>

> [1]: https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/builders/ci/Linux%20CFI/25348/overview

>

> Original change's description:

> > Reland "pthreadpool: Integrate with Jobs API"

> >

> > This is a reland of commit e29465230b2f97fc64d51395bf9353e2ab266570

> >

> > This reland fixes the build issue on win-arm64 bots, such as [1], by

> > declaring the missing arm64 intrinsics if the arm64intr.h is not

> > included correctly due to LLVM issue [2]. Once the LLVM issue is

> > resolved, this work-around should be removed.

> >

> > [1]: https://ci.chromium.org/b/8779781271284246545

> > [2]: https://github.com/llvm/llvm-project/issues/62942

> >

> > Original change's description:

> > > pthreadpool: Integrate with Jobs API

> > >

> > > pthreadpool is used by XNNPACK which in turns supports TFLite and WebNN

> > > to execute each neural network operator of a model by multiple threads

> > > in parallel.

> > >

> > > To avoid creating an unmanaged thread pool owned by pthreadpool

> > > implementation, this CL implements a shim of `pthreadpool_parallelize()`

> > > that maps the pthreadpool thread tasks to work items and uses Jobs API

> > > (`base::PostJob`) to schedule these work items with Chromium's

> > > `base::ThreadPool` workers.

> > >

> > > According to the test result on a multi-core device, when scheduling 4

> > > work items with `base::ThreadPool`, XNNPACK model inference performance

> > > could get ~1.9X speedup for MobileNet V2 and ~2.8X speedup for ResNet50

> > > V2 compared to single thread execution. And the test result also shows

> > > using Jobs API shim could achieve 85% and 97% performance of using

> > > pthreadpool own thread pool implementation for MobileNet V2 and ResNet50

> > > V2 respectively.

> > >

> > > This CL also enables pthreadpool_unittests with Jobs API integration on

> > > Windows and Linux bots that aligns with the `build_tflite_with_xnnpack`

> > > build flag.

entry.title: Prerender: Retrigger UpdateSpeculationCandidates on BFCache restoration
entry.content:
for prerender



Before this CL, speculation rules preloading is not processed again on

the pages restored from BFCache. This CL introduces a feature to

retrigger speculation rules on BFCache restoration for prerender by

retriggering `DocumentSpeculationRules::UpdateSpeculationCandidates()`.



For more information, please see the design doc on crbug.



Note that

- This project tries to target preload(both prefetch/

prerender). This CL focuses on prerender first(Just calling

`UpdateSpeculationCandidates()` is insufficient for the current prefetch

implementation to retrigger).

- This CL focuses on verifying the default prerendering behavior first

(list rules, eagerness is kEager). This CL also expects to be worked

with other prerendering cases and these tests will be added in the

following CL.

- DevTools doesn’t work on BFCache restoration at this CL, but the

reason is a part of crbug.com/1448790 and this CL will maintain

necessary CDP events to work with DevTools.



Bug: 1449163

entry.title: Fix country code parsing
entry.content:
Sometimes websites specify that they deliver a country code via the

autocomplete attribute while the actual value is a country name.

Autofill compensates for that by looking up the country name in a

database but before doing that it tries to interpret the assumed country

code as a 2-letter ASCII code. In some languages, like Japanese, the

corresponding conversion from the country name ("日本") to a ASCII fails

because the name is not ASCII.



This CL makes the code base more robust.



Fixed: 1453848

entry.title: arc: ArcVmDataMigrator: Extend timeout of GetAndroidDataInfo to 3 min
entry.content:
According to the UMA metric

Arc.VmDataMigration.ScreenSetupFailure.OnNewMigration and some user

reports, the migration welcome screen setup sometimes fails because

GetAndroidDataInfo() D-Bus call does not reply within the timeout. In

fact, GetAndroidDataInfo() takes longer as there are more files in the

migration source, and the current timeout (default, 25 seconds) might be

too short for some users on slower device with large pre-migration

/data. This CL thus extends the timeout to 3 minutes.

Note that this change does not ruin the UX, as the current front-end

implementation displays a spinner while waiting for the D-Bus call.



BUG=b:286355468

TEST=Test that the migration welcome screen is set up even when

TEST=GetAndroidDataInfo() takes more than 25 seconds.

entry.title: Fix URL parser's percent decoding to keep valid codepoint chars
entry.content:
This CL is part of URL interop 2023 effort.



This CL includes many rebaseline. Please refer to

https://crrev.com/c/4567772/9 , which is a patch set prior to the

addition of rebaselines. It is easiler to review.



The problem:



When parsing URLs, Chrome replaces certain percent-encoded "invalid"

characters with U+FFFD (Replacement character), even if they are valid

Unicode codepoint characters. This behavior does not comply with the

specification ([1], [2]). The correct behavior is to leave them as-is

as long as the decoded character is a valid Unicode codepoint.



For example, Chrome fails the following test because it replaces

\U+FFFF with U+FFFD:



// URL includes U+FFFF ("0xEF 0xBF 0xBF" in utf-8)

const url = new URL("https://example.com:8080/a?key=%EF%BF%BF");

// Chrome fails because `searchParams.get("key")` returns "\uFFFD".

assertEquals(url.searchParams.get("key"), "\uFFFF");



The term "invalid characters" is used ambiguously in the codebase. We

should differentiate between:



A) Invalid byte sequences in given encoding (e.g. UTF-8 or UTF-16)



B) Valid Unicode codepoints but in some Unicode codepoint ranges that

are not characters (e.g. U+FFFF)



Currently, `ReadUTFChar` defined in url_canon_internal.cc replaces not

only (A) but also (B) with U+FFFD. This CL fixes this behavior so that

only (A) is replaced with U+FFFD.



`ReadUTFChar` is renamed to `ReadUTFCharLossy` to clarify that it

replaces invalid byte sequences with U+FFFD, as Rust's

`String::from_utf8_lossy` does [3].



Interoperability:



- Only Chrome is non-compliant with the spec, while Firefox and Safari

are compliant.

- I have also tested the behavior of relevant Web APIs in non-browser

environments or libraries. Deno's `URLSearchParam` implementation

and Rust's `url` crate [4] are both compliant. Only Chrome's

`URLSearchParam` is non-compliant based on my testing.



History:



I investigated the history of Chrome's current behavior. Using `git

blame`, I found the following CLs and repository:



- https://codereview.chromium.org/250233002

- https://codereview.chromium.org/13821004

- https://code.google.com/archive/p/google-url/



It appears that this behavior has been in place since at least 2013

(the date of the last commit of the google-url library). The URL

Standard and Encoding were likely not available at that time.



Tests:



This change updates existing web tests and unit tests if they rely on

Chrome's non-compliant behavior.



The impacts:



Changing the URL parsing behavior may sound concerning, but I believe

this change can be safely landed without experimentation. Other

browsers and modern URL libraries already comply with the

specification.



The indirect callers of `UTFReadChar` are:



- `DecodeURLEscapeSequences` in url_utils.cc

- `DoConvertToQueryEncoding` in url_canon_query.cc



Therefore, the change's impact should be limited to URL percent

encode/decode. It does not affect the general utf-8/16

encoding/decoding behavior in the codebase.



Rebaseline:



Most rebaselines are understandable, but there is one thing to note

regarding the following line, which appears in several

expectation-text files:



> FAIL assert_equals: protocol expected "http:" but got ":"



This is not a regression. This change makes the original

`assert_equals` pass. Therefore, the subsequent assert_equals failure

is now shown, which should be addressed as a separate issue.





[1]: https://url.spec.whatwg.org/

[2]: https://encoding.spec.whatwg.org/

[3]: https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/string/struct.String.html#method.from_utf8_lossy

[4]: https://docs.rs/url/latest/url/
